 Asia, Europe, North America and the Middle East, contributors question how and why particular forms of political struggle and collective action may, or indeed may not, be carried forward in the context of geographic and social border crossings. In doing so, they bring the dynamic relationship between class, gender, and culture to the forefront in each distinctive migration setting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCulture and globalization. 0aEmigration and immigrationxEconomic aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxPolitical aspects. 0aHuman beingsxMigrations. 0aMigrations of nations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aAbrahamer Rothstein, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarber, Pauline Gardiner, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrance Labrecque, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardiner Barber, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiles, Wenona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeyman, Josiah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeach, Belinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLem, Winnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLem, Winnie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNarotzky, Susana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerò, Davide, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZontini, Elisabetta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184545840940